Here are some of the best photos from 2019:

1. Women in Buenos Aires, Argentina, march on International Women‚Äôs Day on March 8.
2. The scene inside Notre Dame Catherdral in Paris, France, the morning after a fire broke out on April 15.
3. Demonstrators in Venezuela push a bus near the border with Colombia on Feb. 23, as security forces clashed with opposition supporters trying to bring aid shipments into the stricken country.
4. A worker in Venice, Italy, clears a house of excess water on Nov. 20 as the city is hit with the worst flooding in more than half a century due to high tides and fierce winds.
5. A man wears a gas mask at a restaurant in Hong Kong on Oct. 4 following a protest. The frequent use of tear gas by police has been a hallmark of the Hong Kong protests.
6. Former British Prime Minister Theresa May announces her resignation outside 10 Downing Street in London, United Kingdom on May 24 after failing to get her Brexit deal through Parliament.
7. Facebook‚Äôs Mark Zuckerberg waits for the start of a House Financial Services Committee hearing in Washington on oct. 23. The company has been under the spotlight because of concerns about privacy and use of data, as well as its decision not to fact-check political advertising in the runup to the 2020 U.S. presidential election.
8. Student demonstrators hold signs during the U.S. Youth Climate Strike in New York on March 15.
9. Women in Buraidah, Saudi Arabia, photograph their children in a date farm on Aug. 4 as the government unpacks decades of strict religious code to open up the country to new industries such as entertainment.
10. A motorcyclist prepares to lead out a group of riders at a Economic Freedom Fighters rally in Johannesburg, South Africa, on May 8 in a parade.

üöÄ To infinity, and beyond! But first, Mars.

If the first space race was a sprint between the U.S. and Soviet Union competing for prizes of pride and military advantage, the new space race is more like a fun run, with nations and companies working together to reach Mars and the great beyond.

That‚Äôs the U.S., China, EU, Russia and U.A.E. all racing against each other to send robotic rovers, satellites and more to the red planet.

The U.S. has the biggest annual space budget of the bunch, followed by China, which plans to build its own space station by 2022.

Is it worth it? Space is costly and complicated, with small missteps punished by loss of life.

The earlier race to the moon changed life with innovations from nutritional supplements for infant formula to camera sensors for mobile phones.

Gains reaped from deep-space exploration could be even greater: from data transmitted via pulsed laser beams for the ultimate high-speed Internet connection, to medical advances flowing from studies of cosmic radiation.

Who do you think will win the race to Mars?

Nike has released its first sneaker built around @kaepernick7. Sports business reporter Eben Novy-Williams has the details on how much they cost and how to get them.

More than a year after Nike first started using Colin Kaepernick in its controversial ‚ÄòJust Do It‚Äô ads, the company released its first shoe built around the quarterback. The Kaepernick Air Force 1‚Äôs released for $110 and sold out almost immediately within the first 24 hours. It‚Äôs a black low top leather shoe with Kaepernick‚Äôs face on the heel. It also features the date August 14, 2016, the first date that Kaepernick started kneeling to protest police brutality.

The demand for the shoes shows two things: 1. Colin is obviously a popular person from a consumer standpoint and can hold up his own line of shoes and apparel. 2. Nike really cares about marketing itself on the forefront of the big social issues of the time. Remember, they do a lot around female empowerment. And this July, they scrapped the plans to release a July 4th shoe when a number of people including Colin Kaepernick said the design was a little insensitive.

Kaepernick says he‚Äôs in great shape and would like to play again if given the opportunity. In the meantime, he‚Äôs become a vocal voice for civil rights and he‚Äôs donated over a million dollars to charity. As for the shoes, if you really want them, they‚Äôre still available on resale sites. They‚Äôre selling for about $200.

New Zealand‚Äôs Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern first attracted global attention in 2017 when she became the world‚Äôs youngest female prime minister. A year later, she became the second world leader to give birth while in office and the first to take maternity leave. But it was her handling of the Christchurch mosque shooting in March 2019 that propelled her onto front pages around the globe. When a far-right gunman¬†murdered¬†51 Muslims at afternoon prayers in a mosque in Christchurch on March 15, Ardern won praise for her empathy and ability to reach out to the Muslim community. An image of her wearing a hijab in solidarity with those affected by the tragedy gained world-wide coverage. The 39-year-old has also been in hot demand offshore. She was one of 15 women on the cover of British Vogue‚Äôs September issue, edited by the Duchess of Sussex, Meghan Markle, and appeared on The Late Show with Stephen Colbert in the U.S. But as her popularity abroad grew, so did her domestic political problems. Support for Ardern‚Äôs Labour Party began to wane as it failed to deliver on key promises, such as tackling a housing crisis. Her poll rating as preferred prime minister has fallen to 36% from 51% in April, but she remains well ahead of opposition leader Simon Bridges who has a rating of 10%. However, support for Bridges‚Äô National Party has risen to 46%, ahead of Labour on 39%, according to a Colmar Brunton poll late last month. The country‚Äôs next election is due by November 2020.

Notre Dame will miss its first Christmas in centuries due to the devastating April fire.

It soldiered on during the 2 World Wars, but a fire in a time of peace was the tragedy that shuttered the cathedral‚Äôs doors. ‚ÄúSince the French Revolution, the cathedral has always held mass even during World War II,‚Äù says Notre Dame Cathedral Rector Patrick Chauvet.

But there is a spark of hope. After months in darkness, the facade of the cathedral was lit up in November after dusk for the first time since the fire.

As a female tattoo artist in Afghanistan, Soraya Shaheedi receives death threats. Tattoos are still taboo in the country, and single women are often forbidden from touching men who are not family. ‚ÄúI have struggled a lot, even been threatened with death, because people in Afghanistan think doing tattoos is haram,‚Äù she said, using the Arabic word that means '"prohibited by religion." ‚ÄúWhether my customers are men or women doesn‚Äôt matter to me. I do tattoos for both,‚Äù says Shaheedi,  the 26-year-old, divorced single mother. She easily gets both men and women customers, as social attitudes toward tattoos shift and more ink parlors open. It‚Äôs a small, but important change that Shaheedi feels a return of Taliban rule could threaten.

Bryan Russell, a 27-year-old man, is running to become Peru‚Äôs first ever member of parliament with Down Syndrome.

Russell is running on a campaign that focuses on the need for representation and inclusion for a group that generally receives little attention from politicians in his country.

Russell, who studied communications in college, says he decided to run for office because he wants to help people with Down Syndrome so that ‚Äúthey too can have a voice.‚Äù He says he hopes that he can ‚Äúbreak the paradigm‚Äù that people with Down Syndrome can‚Äôt be independent.

Camille Schrier, a biochemist from Virginia, was crowned Miss America on Thursday, minutes after she performed a science experiment during the talent section of the show. The 24-year-old dressed in a lab coat and did a chemistry experiment showing the catalytic decomposition of hydrogen peroxide.

Schrier said she decided to compete for Miss America after the pageant ditched its swimsuit competition and made other changes to modernize the organization. She said she hopes to ‚Äúbreak stereotypes about what it means to be a Miss America in 2020‚Äù by being a ‚Äúwoman of science‚Äù who is authentic to herself.
